</li>
<li id="cite&#95;note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" /><cite id="CITEREFPritchard2014" class="citation journal cs1">Pritchard, David M. (2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/greece-and-rome/article/position-of-attic-women-in-democratic-athens/4A45F942BCEE5E69ACC7ED8AC9EAD1CB">"The Position of Attic Women in Democratic Athens"</a>. <i>Greece &amp; Rome</i>. <b>61</b> (2): <span class="nowrap">174–</span>193. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1017%2FS0017383514000072">10.1017/S0017383514000072</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://search.worldcat.org/issn/0017-3835">0017-3835</a>. <q>And so in legal speeches the names of the wives and the daughters of citizens were usually suppressed and they were referred to by roundabout phrases.</q></cite><span title="ctx&#95;ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft&#95;val&#95;fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Greece+%26+Rome&amp;rft.atitle=The+Position+of+Attic+Women+in+Democratic+Athens&amp;rft.volume=61&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=174-193&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft&#95;id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1017%2FS0017383514000072&amp;rft.issn=0017-3835&amp;rft.aulast=Pritchard&amp;rft.aufirst=David+M.&amp;rft&#95;id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cambridge.org%2Fcore%2Fjournals%2Fgreece-and-rome%2Farticle%2Fposition-of-attic-women-in-democratic-athens%2F4A45F942BCEE5E69ACC7ED8AC9EAD1CB&amp;rfr&#95;id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAthenian+democracy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite&#95;note-41"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" /><cite id="CITEREFJameson1997" class="citation cs2">Jameson, Michael H. (1997), Brulé, Pierre; Oulhen, Jacques (eds.), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.openedition.org/pur/20971">"Women and Democracy in Fourth-century Athens"</a>, <i>Esclavage, guerre, économie en Grèce ancienne&#160;: Hommages à Yvon Garlan</i>, Histoire, Rennes: Presses universitaires de Rennes, pp.&#160;<span class="nowrap">95–</span>107, <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-2-7535-2482-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-2-7535-2482-8"><bdi>978-2-7535-2482-8</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved <span class="nowrap">15 May</span> 2025</span>, <q>Athenian women were ideally silent, anonymous and invisible, except in certain cuit contexts. They were to confine themselves to the house, not even answering a knock on the door and certainly not running out to the street (Menander Fr. 592 Koerte). They were not to associate with unrelated male visitors who came to the house. Their ownership of property was severely limited.</q></cite><span title="ctx&#95;ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft&#95;val&#95;fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Esclavage%2C+guerre%2C+%C3%A9conomie+en+Gr%C3%A8ce+ancienne+%3A+Hommages+%C3%A0+Yvon+Garlan&amp;rft.atitle=Women+and+Democracy+in+Fourth-century+Athens&amp;rft.pages=95-107&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.isbn=978-2-7535-2482-8&amp;rft.aulast=Jameson&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael+H.&amp;rft&#95;id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.openedition.org%2Fpur%2F20971&amp;rfr&#95;id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAthenian+democracy" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
